4
00:00:25,110 --> 00:00:27,196
For God's sake, Izzy.

5
00:00:31,575 --> 00:00:33,577
Here she comes. Let's go.

6
00:00:33,660 --> 00:00:35,746
Come on, man. Come on.

7
00:00:40,459 --> 00:00:42,419
- You gotta be kiddin'.
- What?

8
00:00:43,003 --> 00:00:45,631
"What" me, and you won't go
to no comic-book convention.

9
00:00:45,714 --> 00:00:47,883
I'm 18. I can go anywhere I want.

10
00:00:47,966 --> 00:00:50,510
Yeah, but where you gonna live
when you get back?

11
00:00:50,636 --> 00:00:52,721
Mom, we gotta get goin'.

12
00:00:55,307 --> 00:00:57,851
Drive careful, Booger.
He's the only son I've got.

13
00:00:57,935 --> 00:01:00,145
OK, Mrs B.

14
00:01:29,341 --> 00:01:31,426
<i>(television)</i>

15
00:01:39,142 --> 00:01:41,812
<i>(Jerry Springer) I'll introduce you
to a woman</i>

16
00:01:41,895 --> 00:01:43,814
<i>who was delivered the surprise of her life.</i>

17
00:01:43,897 --> 00:01:46,483
<i>After what seemed like a normal pregnancy,</i>

18
00:01:46,566 --> 00:01:49,611
<i>doctors delivered to Delores
a very special child.</i>

19
00:01:49,695 --> 00:01:51,780
<i>A mother of two beautiful children,</i>

20
00:01:51,863 --> 00:01:57,494
<i>Delores held in her arms a boy with fur
like a dog and a hairline like Eddie Munster.</i>

21
00:01:57,577 --> 00:02:01,665
<i>She's here with us today with her real-life,
but sleeping, wolf baby.</i>

22
00:02:01,748 --> 00:02:04,501
<i>Why not just give him
a razor and some shaving cream?</i>

23
00:02:04,584 --> 00:02:06,670
<i>He'll be shaving in a few years, anyway.</i>

24
00:02:06,753 --> 00:02:10,465
<i>Well, actually, he seems to be
quite allergic to shaving cream.</i>

25
00:02:12,009 --> 00:02:16,263
<i>...seem to like it.
They like to come up and touch his hair.</i>

26
00:02:16,346 --> 00:02:19,766
<i>- So they don't tease him?
- No, he's quite popular.</i>

27
00:02:19,850 --> 00:02:21,727
<i>Dandruff a problem?</i>

28
00:02:21,810 --> 00:02:25,314
<i>No, I wash his hair twice a day,
and brush a hundred strokes a night.</i>

29
00:02:25,397 --> 00:02:27,858
I can't believe this.

30
00:02:27,941 --> 00:02:31,111
<i>I think the question the audience
really wants answered is,</i>

31
00:02:31,194 --> 00:02:33,363
<i>what does the father look like?</i>

32
00:02:33,447 --> 00:02:37,159
<i>- The father is completely bald.
- Completely?</i>

33
00:02:45,083 --> 00:02:48,211
<i>( "The Sun Ain't Gonna Shine Anymore"
by Cher)</i>

34
00:03:07,647 --> 00:03:09,775
<i>Loneliness</i>

35
00:03:09,858 --> 00:03:11,943
Hello?

36
00:03:12,027 --> 00:03:14,696
<i>Is the cloak you wear</i>

37
00:03:14,780 --> 00:03:16,865
Who's there?

38
00:03:16,948 --> 00:03:20,869
<i>A deep shade of blue</i>

39
00:03:20,952 --> 00:03:23,872
<i>ls always there</i>

40
00:03:26,291 --> 00:03:30,420
<i>The sun ain't gonna shine any more</i>

41
00:03:30,504 --> 00:03:34,674
<i>The moon ain't gonna rise in the sky</i>

42
00:03:34,758 --> 00:03:40,222
<i>The tears are always clouding your eyes</i>

43
00:03:40,305 --> 00:03:45,936
<i>When you're without love</i>

44
00:04:22,347 --> 00:04:26,560
<i>(Scully)</i> "Dear Special Agent Mulder,
I'm writing to you for help."

45
00:04:26,643 --> 00:04:30,188
"Several years ago,
I had an experience I could not explain."

46
00:04:30,272 --> 00:04:33,150
"I was lying in my bed
when I felt a presence in the room."

47
00:04:33,233 --> 00:04:37,529
"Though I was awake, I felt that something
had taken control over my body."

48
00:04:37,612 --> 00:04:43,201
"I don't remember much else, but I woke up
three days later pregnant with my son lzzy."

49
00:04:46,997 --> 00:04:50,041
"That was 18 years ago,
but now it happened again."

50
00:04:50,125 --> 00:04:53,462
"I was in bed,
and could swear I heard Cher singing."

51
00:04:54,463 --> 00:04:56,423
"The one who was married to Sonny."

52
00:04:57,924 --> 00:05:01,511
"Then the room got all smoky
and I saw some kind of monster."

53
00:05:01,595 --> 00:05:05,140
"He had a really gross face
with lumps all over his head."

54
00:05:05,223 --> 00:05:09,436
"I was too scared to scream. Then I got
all groggy and conked out for three days."

55
00:05:09,519 --> 00:05:11,646
"Guess what happened when I woke up."

56
00:05:11,730 --> 00:05:13,857
"I got your name off the

57
00:05:13,940 --> 00:05:18,069
"Some lady on the <i>Jerry</i> Springer Show
who had a werewolf baby

58
00:05:18,153 --> 00:05:20,280
said you came to her house."

59
00:05:21,281 --> 00:05:24,951
"I got her story beat by a mile,
so maybe you'll want to come see me, too."

60
00:05:25,035 --> 00:05:27,454
"Sincerely, Shaineh Berkowitz."

61
00:05:27,537 --> 00:05:31,416
Scully, do you think it's too soon
to get my own 1-900 number?

62
00:05:39,841 --> 00:05:43,220
Did you actually see that werewolf baby
or was that just a story?

63
00:05:43,303 --> 00:05:46,598
No, it had something
called hypertrichosis lanuginosa.

64
00:05:46,681 --> 00:05:48,975
It's a rare hereditary condition,

65
00:05:49,059 --> 00:05:52,062
most commonly found
in some South American families.

66
00:05:52,145 --> 00:05:55,774
Uh-huh. But it was all hairy and stuff?

67
00:05:55,857 --> 00:06:00,195
Uh, Mrs Berkowitz,
you said that you also had a son?

68
00:06:00,445 --> 00:06:02,614
Mm-hm. Izzy. That's him there.

69
00:06:04,824 --> 00:06:09,371
And Izzy is the product of
your union with some kind of intruder?

70
00:06:09,496 --> 00:06:13,041
I don't know about no "union",
but I sure woke up in a condition.

71
00:06:13,291 --> 00:06:16,378
- Did you report this to the police?
- Of course I did.

72
00:06:16,461 --> 00:06:18,630
Was there an investigation?

73
00:06:18,713 --> 00:06:21,841
Not really.
Nobody here ever locks their doors.

74
00:06:21,925 --> 00:06:25,262
And it took me a month or two
to figure it out - that I was pregnant.

75
00:06:25,345 --> 00:06:27,347
And now you're pregnant again?

76
00:06:27,430 --> 00:06:32,435
Uh-huh. But as I told Agent Mulder
on the phone, that's what takes the cake.

77
00:06:32,519 --> 00:06:35,647
Mrs Berkowitz had
a tubal ligation two years ago.

78
00:06:36,815 --> 00:06:40,902
You can't plant a seed in a barren field.

79
00:06:41,236 --> 00:06:43,613
They were cookin' somethin' on the range.

80
00:06:43,697 --> 00:06:47,242
Took me two days
of scrubbin' to clean the skillet.

81
00:06:49,661 --> 00:06:52,539
I don't know how many
of 'em there were. I only saw one,

82
00:06:52,622 --> 00:06:54,666
but they ate a whole jar of peanut butter.

83
00:06:54,749 --> 00:06:57,377
You were gone three days,
but nobody missed you?

84
00:06:57,460 --> 00:07:00,964
- I know what you're thinkin'.
- Do you drink, Mrs Berkowitz?

85
00:07:01,047 --> 00:07:05,635
No. But I'm not so sure my intruders,
as you call 'em, didn't have a few.

86
00:07:07,262 --> 00:07:10,765
Somebody set a tumbler here
and didn't use no coaster.

87
00:07:12,517 --> 00:07:14,477
That's a family heirloom, too.

88
00:07:14,561 --> 00:07:17,188
Is there no chance
your son could've put it there?

89
00:07:17,272 --> 00:07:21,401
Izzy's got more brains than that.
Not much more, but he values his life.

90
00:07:21,484 --> 00:07:24,154
That pigsty there's his room.

91
00:07:27,741 --> 00:07:30,619
You know what this thing is,
don't you, Agent Mulder?

92
00:07:30,702 --> 00:07:34,372
- Why do you say that?
- Because. You're all quiet and stuff.

93
00:07:34,706 --> 00:07:39,002
And you know somethin'
you're not sayin' - about alien abductions.

94
00:07:39,085 --> 00:07:42,130
They said on <i>Jerry</i> Springer
you're, like, an expert.

95
00:07:42,213 --> 00:07:45,967
Well, I don't think this has
anything to do with alien abductions.

96
00:07:46,051 --> 00:07:49,888
- I don't know if I believe in that any more.
- Oh, come on!

97
00:07:49,971 --> 00:07:52,223
- Really?
- Mrs Berkowitz?

98
00:07:53,224 --> 00:07:55,435
You gave a description of the intruder,

99
00:07:55,518 --> 00:07:58,104
saying he had a gross face
and lumps on his head?

100
00:07:58,188 --> 00:08:00,815
And two mouths.
I don't know if I mentioned that.

101
00:08:00,899 --> 00:08:03,652
Funny. Sounds just like this.

102
00:08:12,994 --> 00:08:15,413
Oh, that?

103
00:08:15,538 --> 00:08:17,457
That's the Great Mutato.

104
00:08:17,749 --> 00:08:20,460
That's a comic-book character
my kid Izzy created.

105
00:08:20,543 --> 00:08:22,962
<i>(door opens)</i>

106
00:08:25,006 --> 00:08:26,216
What's goin' on?

107
00:08:26,299 --> 00:08:29,427
These are Agents Mulder
and Scully from the FBI.

108
00:08:30,011 --> 00:08:32,097
The Federal Bureau of Investigation?

109
00:08:32,180 --> 00:08:37,727
We were wondering how this suspect
in your mother's case looks exactly like this.

110
00:08:37,811 --> 00:08:41,690
- The Great Mutato.
- Because I've seen him too.

111
00:08:42,357 --> 00:08:44,609
You've seen the Great Mutato?

112
00:08:44,693 --> 00:08:46,986
Yeah. A lot of people around here have.

113
00:08:47,070 --> 00:08:50,240
Has it crossed neither of your minds
that what you say you saw

114
00:08:50,323 --> 00:08:53,660
fits perfectly with
this creature that your son created?

115
00:08:53,743 --> 00:08:55,829
Well, yeah, but...

116
00:08:57,122 --> 00:08:59,290
that don't mean it didn't happen.

117
00:09:07,757 --> 00:09:10,009
Don't ask me why, but it works.

118
00:09:14,931 --> 00:09:16,558
Peanut butter sandwiches?

119
00:09:16,641 --> 00:09:18,810
You think bologna would be more effective?

120
00:09:18,893 --> 00:09:20,562
Why are you humouring them, Mulder?

121
00:09:20,645 --> 00:09:24,816
I'm not, Scully. This is a very serious crime.

122
00:09:24,899 --> 00:09:29,696
So is perjury. So is calling out
FBI agents under false pretenses.

123
00:09:29,779 --> 00:09:32,657
- For the purpose of what?
- Isn't it obvious?

124
00:09:33,575 --> 00:09:36,995
I think what we're seeing here
is an example of a culture

125
00:09:37,078 --> 00:09:40,123
for whom daytime talk shows
and tabloid headlines

126
00:09:40,206 --> 00:09:43,752
have become a reality
against which they measure their lives.

127
00:09:43,835 --> 00:09:47,547
A culture so obsessed by the media
and a chance for self-dramatisation

128
00:09:47,630 --> 00:09:49,966
that they'll do anything
to gain a spotlight.

129
00:09:50,049 --> 00:09:53,720
I am alarmed that you would reduce
these people to a cultural stereotype.

130
00:09:53,803 --> 00:09:56,931
Not everybody's dream
is to get on <i>Jerry</i> Springer.

131
00:09:57,640 --> 00:10:01,144
Psychologists often speak of
the denial of an unthinkable evil

132
00:10:01,227 --> 00:10:03,855
or a misplacement of shared fears.

133
00:10:03,938 --> 00:10:06,858
Anxieties taking the form
of a hideous monster

134
00:10:06,941 --> 00:10:10,945
for whom the most horrific
human attributes can be ascribed.

135
00:10:11,029 --> 00:10:14,282
What... what we can't
possibly imagine ourselves capable of,

136
00:10:14,365 --> 00:10:19,954
we can blame on the ogre,
on the hunchback, on the lowly half-breed.

137
00:10:20,038 --> 00:10:21,456
<i>(clears throat)</i>

138
00:10:23,208 --> 00:10:29,255
Common sense will tell you these legends,
these unverified rumours, are ridiculous.

139
00:10:29,339 --> 00:10:31,591
But nonetheless, unverifiable,

140
00:10:31,674 --> 00:10:35,011
and thus true, in the sense
that they're believed to be true.

141
00:10:35,094 --> 00:10:37,263
Is there anything you don't believe in?

142
00:10:37,347 --> 00:10:39,432
' <i>(moaning)
- Sh!</i>

143
00:10:44,896 --> 00:10:46,981
<i>(moaning)</i>

144
00:10:47,857 --> 00:10:50,360
What's that sound?

145
00:10:52,403 --> 00:10:54,572
It's the Great Mutato!

146
00:11:33,486 --> 00:11:36,948
- Where'd it go?
- I don't know. I lost it.

147
00:11:40,493 --> 00:11:42,871
There. Up there.

148
00:11:46,249 --> 00:11:48,334
Turn that damn thing off!

149
00:11:52,881 --> 00:11:55,008
You're on my property.

150
00:11:55,091 --> 00:11:57,218
We're with the FBI.

151
00:11:57,302 --> 00:11:59,721
- They're not.
- We were...

152
00:12:00,763 --> 00:12:03,558
We were chasing
what they told us was a monster.

153
00:12:03,892 --> 00:12:07,270
Monster? What did I tell you boys?

154
00:12:08,229 --> 00:12:10,315
There ain't no monster.

155
00:12:10,607 --> 00:12:13,568
I'll show you the monster you're lookin' for.

156
00:12:16,362 --> 00:12:18,448
- Who sent you here?
- Your father.

157
00:12:18,531 --> 00:12:20,783
My father is a simpleton farmer.

158
00:12:20,867 --> 00:12:23,995
He understands nothing
of my scientific achievements.

159
00:12:24,078 --> 00:12:28,166
- What achievements are those?
- What makes you think you'd understand?

160
00:12:28,249 --> 00:12:30,251
Well, I'm a scientist, for one.

161
00:12:30,335 --> 00:12:34,672
Then you probably know that once
in a generation, perhaps once in a lifetime,

162
00:12:34,756 --> 00:12:39,344
a truth is uncovered which thrusts mankind
into a shocking new consciousness,

163
00:12:39,427 --> 00:12:42,972
turning accepted notions
of our very existence on their head.

164
00:12:43,056 --> 00:12:47,644
Consider relativity. The double helix.
And now the homeotic hox gene,

165
00:12:47,727 --> 00:12:51,856
for which I will undoubtedly have my place
among the Columbuses of science

166
00:12:51,940 --> 00:12:54,108
as a visionary leader of men, yes?

167
00:12:54,192 --> 00:12:57,070
What do you want me
to do with these, Dr Polidori?

168
00:13:01,491 --> 00:13:03,493
Never mind.

169
00:13:03,576 --> 00:13:06,663
What is the homeotic hox gene?

170
00:13:08,122 --> 00:13:11,459
She's a scientist. Ask her.

171
00:13:11,542 --> 00:13:18,591
I, uh... I believe that it has something
to do with, um... growth and development.

172
00:13:18,675 --> 00:13:21,678
If you two will excuse me,
I don't have time for this.

173
00:13:21,761 --> 00:13:25,556
I have to travel to the University
of lngolstadt to deliver an address.

174
00:13:25,640 --> 00:13:28,851
Sir, unless you want
your scientific achievements

175
00:13:28,935 --> 00:13:31,229
to end up as a footnote
on the <i>Jerry</i> Springer Show,

176
00:13:31,312 --> 00:13:34,232
I suggest that you make the time.

177
00:13:36,317 --> 00:13:38,778
<i>Jerry Springer Show?</i>

178
00:13:39,862 --> 00:13:42,907
Witness the morphogenesis of drosophila.

179
00:13:43,825 --> 00:13:46,452
The fruit fly.

180
00:13:46,536 --> 00:13:50,123
What you are watching
has been going on for millennia -

181
00:13:50,206 --> 00:13:53,793
since the Cambrian period
some 580 million short years ago,

182
00:13:53,876 --> 00:13:55,712
when drosophila was first born.

183
00:13:55,795 --> 00:13:58,423
See the elegant symmetry
with which the pupa grows

184
00:13:58,506 --> 00:14:01,426
into a series of beautiful segments.

185
00:14:03,678 --> 00:14:06,014
What we have found...

186
00:14:06,097 --> 00:14:08,474
what I have found

187
00:14:08,558 --> 00:14:11,894
is that these segments
represent a linear model

188
00:14:11,978 --> 00:14:15,023
for the genetic development
of our friend the fly.

189
00:14:16,107 --> 00:14:17,608
Each gene is responsible

190
00:14:17,692 --> 00:14:19,694
for the development
of its corresponding segment-

191
00:14:19,777 --> 00:14:22,947
the legs, the mouth,
the body, posterior and anterior -

192
00:14:23,740 --> 00:14:29,454
but which I, through my genius,
can alter into a creation of my own.

193
00:14:30,038 --> 00:14:34,042
Behold, proboscopedia.

194
00:14:43,051 --> 00:14:45,219
This fly has legs...

195
00:14:45,511 --> 00:14:47,513
Growing out of his mouth.

196
00:14:51,768 --> 00:14:53,853
Why would you do that?

197
00:14:54,353 --> 00:14:56,439
Because I can.

198
00:14:57,482 --> 00:14:59,567
Could that be done in humans?

199
00:14:59,650 --> 00:15:02,403
That would go against
every scientific convention.

200
00:15:02,487 --> 00:15:04,947
But could it be done?

201
00:15:05,031 --> 00:15:07,116
Theoretically.

202
00:15:17,877 --> 00:15:19,962
Good night, Dr Frankenstein.

203
00:15:21,422 --> 00:15:24,050
Despite what you might think, Mulder,

204
00:15:24,133 --> 00:15:27,637
designer mutations like these
are virtually impossible on humans.

205
00:15:27,720 --> 00:15:30,973
- That's not what I just heard.
- Mulder, even if they could,

206
00:15:31,057 --> 00:15:35,144
no scientist would even dare to perform
these kind of experiments on a human.

207
00:15:35,228 --> 00:15:39,398
- Well, then, why do them at all?
- To... unlock the mysteries of genetics.

208
00:15:39,482 --> 00:15:42,318
To understand why,
even though we share the same genes,

209
00:15:42,401 --> 00:15:44,737
we develop arms instead of wings,

210
00:15:44,821 --> 00:15:48,741
we become humans instead of flies,
or monsters.

211
00:15:48,991 --> 00:15:53,913
But given the power, who could resist the
temptation to create life in his own image?

212
00:15:53,996 --> 00:15:58,376
We already have that ability, Mulder.
It's called procreation.

213
00:15:58,459 --> 00:16:00,128
And first thing tomorrow morning,

214
00:16:00,211 --> 00:16:03,631
I'm gonna verify the pregnancy
of Shaineh Berkowitz.

215
00:16:19,814 --> 00:16:22,900
- When are you 00min' home again?
- Huh?

216
00:16:22,984 --> 00:16:25,486
- When are you 00min' home again?
- What?

217
00:16:25,653 --> 00:16:28,364
- We were gonna have that talk.
- Soon.

218
00:16:28,447 --> 00:16:31,951
- Soon. We'll have our talk soon.
- That's what you always say.

219
00:16:32,034 --> 00:16:35,079
Elizabeth, you know
how I feel about children.

220
00:16:36,372 --> 00:16:40,418
- They're mewling little monsters.
- But I want children.

221
00:16:41,002 --> 00:16:43,296
What happened to our dream?

222
00:16:43,379 --> 00:16:47,425
Of getting out of this place,
getting away from this hick town?

223
00:16:47,508 --> 00:16:49,844
I think that's your dream.

224
00:16:49,927 --> 00:16:53,723
Elizabeth, what do you want?
A baby? Or a Nobel prize?

225
00:16:56,726 --> 00:16:58,811
See you on Thursday.

226
00:17:22,793 --> 00:17:24,879
<i>(Sobs)</i>

227
00:18:22,520 --> 00:18:24,730
Hot plates! Hot, hot, hot!

228
00:18:24,814 --> 00:18:30,695
Biscuits, fritters, grits, flapjacks,
eggs - boiled, scrambled, poached and fried.

229
00:18:30,778 --> 00:18:33,030
We got some monster grapefruits
on the way.

230
00:18:33,114 --> 00:18:34,949
Bigger than your head, almost.

